        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Dragon­fly (bot­tom), mon­i­tor lizard, sun skink (be­low), sea ap­ple tree, wild ixora</p>
    <p>• This re­lax­ing route is suit­able for fam­i­lies with young chil­dren.</p>
    <p>The views are gor­geous, with the reservoir ’s calm sur­face re­flect­ing the clouds that go by, all set against a sooth­ing back­drop of dense rain­for­est.</p>
    <p>• If you look closely, you can even see fish and other crea­tures in the wa­ter. I spot a mon­i­tor lizard tak­ing a dip in the reservoir’s placid wa­ters.</p>
    <p>• The signs along the trail of­fer de­light­ful bits of trivia. One teaches me how to dif­fer­en­ti­ate be­tween but­ter­flies and moths – but­ter­flies usu­ally rest with their wings closed, while moths usu­ally do so with their wings open – while an­other ex­plains that the reservoir might ap­pear green­ish be­cause of the pres­ence of al­gae and phy­to­plank­ton.</p>

